The histogram shows that there are very few values close to 4.3 cm and values above 7.5 cm are also relatively rare.

  1. Sepal width (cm):
  • Min : 2
  • Max : 4.4

  • median : 3
  • Q1 : 2.8

The quartiles show that the majority of the data is concentrated around the median values, with few extreme values. The histogram shows a very prominent peak around 3.0 cm, which is consistent with the median and the mean. There is a significant concentration of values between 2.5 cm and 3.5 cm, indicating that most of the samples have a sepal width close to this range.

The distribution of petal length shows a wide range, from 1.0 to 6.9 cm. In the histogram, the values appear relatively spread out, with two noticeable peaks at 1.4 cm and 1.5 cm, each representing 13 samples (8.7%).

  1. Petal width (cm):

The distribution of petal width has a relatively large range, from 0.1 to 2.5 cm. In the histogram, the values appear fairly evenly distributed, although there is a noticeable peak at 0.2 cm, representing 29 samples (19.3%).

  1. Species:
  • Categorical, representing the species of Iris flowers:
    • Iris setosa
    • Iris versicolor
    • Iris virginica
  • Iris setosa: 50 samples
  • Iris versicolor: 50 samples
  • Iris virginica: 50 samples

We observe that the species are evenly distributed across the dataset, with each class containing 50 samples, making a total of 150 samples.

Analysis of Key Correlations with Species:

  • Petal width (cm): 92%

    Very High Positive Correlation: The correlation between petal width and species is strong and positive. This indicates that as the petal width increases, the likelihood of identifying a specific species (such as Iris virginica) increases significantly. Petal width is one of the most reliable features in distinguishing between species.

  • Petal length (cm): 89%

    High Positive Correlation: Petal length also shows a strong positive correlation with species. Similar to petal width, as the petal length increases, certain species (such as Iris virginica) are more likely to be identified. This makes petal length another important feature for classification.

  • Sepal length (cm): 62%

    Moderate Positive Correlation: Sepal length has a moderate positive correlation with species. While it is not as strong a predictor as petal dimensions, sepal length still plays a meaningful role in differentiating between species, particularly between Iris setosa and the other two species.

  • Sepal width (cm): 45%

    Low Positive Correlation: Sepal width shows a weaker correlation with species compared to the other features. Although it still contributes to the classification, it is less influential in distinguishing between the different species of Iris flowers.

Part 4: Classification Task

Create the training and test sets.

In[7]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X = iris_df.drop(columns=['species'])
y = iris_df['species']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

Preprocess the dataset

In[8]:
from sklearn import preprocessing
scaler = preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit(X_train)
X_scaled = scaler.transform(X_train)

Train a logistic regression classifier

In[9]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
# Initialize the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=200);
# Train the model on the training data
model.fit(X_train, y_train);
In[10]:
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

Evaluate the Model

In[11]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=['setosa', 'versicolor', 'virginica'])

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")
print("Classification Report:\n")
print(report)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for i, coef in enumerate(coefs):
    plt.plot(feature_names, coef, marker='o', label=f'{coef_df.index[i]} Coefficients')

In[13]:
import numpy as np

def draw_coef_vectors(ax, coef, feature_names):
    norms = np.linalg.norm(coef, axis=1)
    coef_normalized = coef / norms[:, np.newaxis]
    
    for i, feature in enumerate(feature_names):
        xlim = ax.get_xlim()
        ylim = ax.get_ylim()
        
        x, y = np.linspace(xlim[0], xlim[1], 2), np.linspace(ylim[0], ylim[1], 2)
        X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
        
        for j in range(coef.shape[0]):
            ax.quiver(X.mean(), Y.mean(), coef_normalized[j, i], coef_normalized[j, (i+1) % 2],
                      angles='xy', scale_units='xy', scale=1, color=f'C{j}', label=f'Class {j+1}')

g = sns.pairplot(X_train)

for ax in g.axes.flatten():
    draw_coef_vectors(ax, coefs, feature_names)

plt.title('Pairplot with Coefficient Vectors')
plt.show()

intercepts = model.intercept_

g = sns.pairplot(X_train)
plt.title('Pairplot of Features')

def plot_intercepts(ax, intercepts, feature_names):
    xlim = ax.get_xlim()
    ylim = ax.get_ylim()
    
    if len(feature_names) == 2:
        for i, intercept in enumerate(intercepts):
            ax.axhline(y=intercept, color=f'C{i}', linestyle='--', label=f'{coef_df.index[i]} Intercept (Horizontal)')
            ax.axvline(x=intercept, color=f'C{i}', linestyle='--', label=f'{coef_df.index[i]} Intercept (Vertical)')
    else:
        pass

for ax in g.axes.flatten():
    plot_intercepts(ax, intercepts, feature_names)

plt.title('Pairplot with Intercepts')
plt.show()
